this other extreme of monopoly

00:02:28.780 --> 00:02:30.460
which gives us a lot
of the insights we

00:02:30.460 --> 00:02:35.070
need for oligopoly but
in a much simpler case.

00:02:35.070 --> 00:02:38.880
Now, the key thing with
monopoly, the key difference

00:02:38.880 --> 00:02:42.150
from what we've done so
far is that now firms

00:02:42.150 --> 00:02:46.200
are going to be price
makers, not price takers.

00:02:46.200 --> 00:02:48.900
That's going to be the key
change from the perfectly

00:02:48.900 --> 00:02:49.830
competitive situation.

00:02:49.830 --> 00:02:51.660
The perfectly
competitive situation,

00:02:51.660 --> 00:02:53.700
from any given
firm's perspective

00:02:53.700 --> 00:02:56.280
the price is something given
them by the great market.

00:02:56.280 --> 00:02:58.170
OK, we talked with
our two diagrams side

00:02:58.170 --> 00:03:01.170
by side about how the
market gives the price.

00:03:01.170 --> 00:03:03.810
But we sort of-- from any
given firm's perspective

00:03:03.810 --> 00:03:05.190
they were price taker.

00:03:05.190 --> 00:03:06.880
They couldn't affect the price.

00:03:06.880 --> 00:03:10.260
Monopolists however,
when you're the only firm

00:03:10.260 --> 00:03:12.330
you get to set the price.

00:03:12.330 --> 00:03:16.260
So monopolists are going to be
price makers, not price takers.

00:03:16.260 --> 00:03:19.980
And that's going to change the
dynamics of everything we do,

00:03:19.980 --> 00:03:23.020
and that'll be our
focus today, OK?

00:03:23.020 --> 00:03:25.750
So that's going to
be the big change,

00:03:25.750 --> 00:03:30.520
we'll go from competitive
markets to monopoly markets.

00:03:30.520 --> 00:03:35.410
Now, for the first 2/3
or 3/4 of the lecture

00:03:35.410 --> 00:03:37.430
we're going to make
one other assumption.

00:03:37.430 --> 00:03:43.120
We are going to assume there is
one price in this market, that

00:03:43.120 --> 00:03:46.148
is no price discrimination.

00:03:48.840 --> 00:03:51.810
This monopolist sets
the price, but he

00:03:51.810 --> 00:03:54.240
sets one price for everybody.

00:03:54.240 --> 00:03:56.550
So if a monopolist
is selling a good,

00:03:56.550 --> 00:04:00.350
they sell that at one price
to everybody buys the good.

00:04:00.350 --> 00:04:02.557
Now once again, this
is not super realistic,

00:04:02.557 --> 00:04:04.640
monopolists often have
different prices for goods.

00:04:04.640 --> 00:04:06.827
But it's a very important,
helpful extreme.

00:04:06.827 --> 00:04:09.410
And you've got to remember that
we're imposing this constraint

00:04:09.410 --> 00:04:11.285
because it's going to
drive the intuition I'm

00:04:11.285 --> 00:04:12.440
going to come to next, OK?

00:04:12.440 --> 00:04:15.380
So you're a firm selling
a good at one price.

00:04:15.380 --> 00:04:20.019
You offer it up, anybody can
buy it at that price, OK?

00:04:20.019 --> 00:04:22.300
Now, what we're going to do--

00:04:22.300 --> 00:04:26.010
if you remember, a mon-- the
fundamental part of producer

00:04:26.010 --> 00:04:27.910
that holds is the
goal of monopolists

00:04:27.910 --> 00:04:35.320
is to maximize his profits, OK,
which is revenues minus costs.

00:04:35.320 --> 00:04:37.330
And as we showed
before, profits are

00:04:37.330 --> 00:04:42.320
maximized when marginal
revenue equals marginal cost.

00:04:42.320 --> 00:04:45.710
That's the profit
maximization point.

00:04:45.710 --> 00:04:49.160
Now, nothing on the cost
side is going to change.

00:04:49.160 --> 00:04:54.200
So monopolish monopolist,
the way we get cost curves

00:04:54.200 --> 00:04:54.893
doesn't change.

00:04:54.893 --> 00:04:56.810
That's all about--
remember, because that just

00:04:56.810 --> 00:04:59.670
comes the technology
production and that

00:04:59.670 --> 00:05:02.512
comes from input prices.

00:05:02.512 --> 00:05:04.470
So nothing on the cost
side is going to change.

00:05:04.470 --> 00:05:06.300
All that hard and
somewhat boring

00:05:06.300 --> 00:05:09.470
work we did deriving
cost functions and stuff,

00:05:09.470 --> 00:05:11.490
that all is-- that's done.

00:05:11.490 --> 00:05:13.740
The only place monopoly gets
exciting is on the margin

00:05:13.740 --> 00:05:17.010
revenue side, because before we
said marginal revenue was just

00:05:17.010 --> 00:05:19.500
price for a price taker.

00:05:19.500 --> 00:05:21.640
But that's no longer true.

00:05:21.640 --> 00:05:24.303
Marginal revenue is
no longer just price.

00:05:24.303 --> 00:05:26.470
Now marginal revenue's going
to be more interesting.

00:05:26.470 --> 00:05:29.020
So the monopoly
difference, if you will,

00:05:29.020 --> 00:05:31.890
or the imperfect
competition difference,

00:05:31.890 --> 00:05:34.032
doesn't come at all
from the cost side.

00:05:34.032 --> 00:05:36.240
That side is done, doesn't
matter what kind of market

00:05:36.240 --> 00:05:38.650
you're looking at, OK?

00:05:38.650 --> 00:05:40.120
All the interesting
action here is

00:05:40.120 --> 00:05:43.480
on the revenue side as we think
about monopoly and oligopoly

00:05:43.480 --> 00:05:45.280
markets, OK?

00:05:45.280 --> 00:05:48.910
So to think about that,
let's go to figure 11-1.

00:05:52.870 --> 00:05:55.370
Think about-- let's start by
think about a competitive firm.

00:05:55.370 --> 00:05:56.825
This is a diagram I
could have shown earlier.

00:05:56.825 --> 00:05:59.450
It just sort of is a way to
think about a competitive firm.

00:05:59.450 --> 00:06:02.840
Think about a competitive
firm's profits.

00:06:02.840 --> 00:06:06.260
So imagine that this firm--

00:06:06.260 --> 00:06:10.340
to make life easy
let's imagine that we

00:06:10.340 --> 00:06:15.080
have a firm with
marginal cost of 0, OK?

00:06:15.080 --> 00:06:20.660
So you've got demand curve, and
so therefore any money you make

00:06:20.660 --> 00:06:21.680
is profit.

00:06:21.680 --> 00:06:22.982
And we're in the short run, OK?

00:06:22.982 --> 00:06:24.440
So there's profit
in the short run,

00:06:24.440 --> 00:06:26.820
even for this perfectly
competitive firm.

00:06:26.820 --> 00:06:29.430
But a perfectly competitive
firm faces a horizontal demand

00:06:29.430 --> 00:06:30.160
curve.

00:06:30.160 --> 00:06:34.770
So if they sell
q units, OK, they

00:06:34.770 --> 00:06:38.010
make profits of area
a, which is simply

00:06:38.010 --> 00:06:41.700
q times P1, little q times P1.

00:06:41.700 --> 00:06:44.130
If they sell q
plus 1 units, they

00:06:44.130 --> 00:06:46.980
make an extra profit
rectangle of B.

00:06:46.980 --> 00:06:49.860
So literally, the marginal--
the extra profit they make

00:06:49.860 --> 00:06:54.840
is just the amount
P. It's 1 times P1.

00:06:54.840 --> 00:06:58.190
The horizontal distance
from q to q plus 1 is 1,

00:06:58.190 --> 00:07:00.390
the vertical distance is P1.

00:07:00.390 --> 00:07:03.358
So the marginal profit
is just the price, OK?

00:07:03.358 --> 00:07:05.400
Marginal revenue, I'm
sorry, it's just the price.

00:07:05.400 --> 00:07:06.352
Yeah?

00:07:06.352 --> 00:07:08.310
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
competitive [INAUDIBLE]..

00:07:08.310 --> 00:07:10.800
JONATHAN GRUBER: Once it's in
the short run there can be,

00:07:10.800 --> 00:07:11.010
right?

00:07:11.010 --> 00:07:12.600
In the short run there can be
profit in a competitive market.

00:07:12.600 --> 00:07:14.868
In the long run
there's no profit, OK?

00:07:14.868 --> 00:07:16.410
So basically, their
marginal revenue,

00:07:16.410 --> 00:07:21.390
what they make-- that next unit
they make is the price, OK?

00:07:21.390 --> 00:07:25.810
Now let's think about
a monopoly firm.

00:07:25.810 --> 00:07:31.410
A monopoly firm does not face a
perfectly elastic demand curve

00:07:31.410 --> 00:07:34.590
because a monopoly firm's demand
curve is the whole market.

00:07:34.590 --> 00:07:38.970
Notice little q has become
big Q on the x-axis.

00:07:38.970 --> 00:07:41.910
The monopolist no longer faces
only their perfectly elastic

00:07:41.910 --> 00:07:43.230
firm demand.

00:07:43.230 --> 00:07:46.710
They face a market demand, which
can be any degree of elasticity

00:07:46.710 --> 00:07:48.270
but typically is
somewhat elastic.

00:07:48.270 --> 00:07:50.350
It's downward sloping.

00:07:50.350 --> 00:07:51.910
Now let's say
you're a monopolist

00:07:51.910 --> 00:07:56.070
and you're selling big
Q units at a price P1.

00:07:56.070 --> 00:08:00.530
Your profits are C plus A. Once
again, same marginal cost of 0

00:08:00.530 --> 00:08:03.060
to make this easy, or C plus A.

00:08:03.060 --> 00:08:06.050
Now let's say you want
to sell one more unit.

00:08:06.050 --> 00:08:07.720
Well, what's different?

00:08:07.720 --> 00:08:09.420
What's different is
now you're facing

00:08:09.420 --> 00:08:11.770
a downward sloping demand curve.

00:08:11.770 --> 00:08:13.950
So if you want to
sell one more unit

00:08:13.950 --> 00:08:16.800
you have to lower the price.

00:08:16.800 --> 00:08:18.390
That's the difference.

00:08:18.390 --> 00:08:20.520
If you want to
sell another unit,

00:08:20.520 --> 00:08:23.880
you can only do so by
lowering the price.

00:08:23.880 --> 00:08:26.490
And you're a price maker, so
you have the right to do that.

00:08:26.490 --> 00:08:27.990
So if you want to
sell another unit,

00:08:27.990 --> 00:08:30.610
two things are going to happen.

00:08:30.610 --> 00:08:33.789
A, you are going to
sell a second unit

00:08:33.789 --> 00:08:35.110
and make money on that unit.

00:08:35.110 --> 00:08:38.539
That's the area B.

00:08:38.539 --> 00:08:40.380
But b-- I should
say one and two.

00:08:40.380 --> 00:08:41.630
One, you sell the second unit.

00:08:41.630 --> 00:08:43.415
That's the area B.

00:08:43.415 --> 00:08:46.040
Two, you will lose money
all the other units

00:08:46.040 --> 00:08:50.030
you sold because now you
have to lower the price.

00:08:50.030 --> 00:08:54.210
Because remember, there's
only one price, OK?

00:08:54.210 --> 00:08:57.920
So basically, you
used to make A plus C.

00:08:57.920 --> 00:09:04.010
Now you make A plus B. You've
added B, but you've lost C.

00:09:04.010 --> 00:09:06.080
So what is the marginal revenue?

00:09:06.080 --> 00:09:08.390
The marginal revenue
for a monopolist

00:09:08.390 --> 00:09:16.415
is now the area B minus the
area C. Or P2, which is area B--

00:09:16.415 --> 00:09:24.860
1 times P2 minus
P2 minus P1 minus

00:09:24.860 --> 00:09:30.140
P2 times Q0, the
original quantity.

00:09:30.140 --> 00:09:31.530
OK?

00:09:31.530 --> 00:09:33.420
This is the area C,
but this is the area

00:09:33.420 --> 00:09:38.330
B. The original quantity
times the change in price.

00:09:38.330 --> 00:09:40.670
So your marginal revenue is
not this simple just priced

00:09:40.670 --> 00:09:41.253
more and more.

00:09:41.253 --> 00:09:44.690
Now it's this more
complicated term, OK?

00:09:44.690 --> 00:09:48.710
More generally, marginal
revenue can be defined

00:09:48.710 --> 00:09:53.810
as-- the marginal
revenue is defined as--

00:09:53.810 --> 00:10:04.630
marginal revenue is defined as
P plus delta P delta Q times Q.

00:10:04.630 --> 00:10:08.200
That's marginal revenue.

00:10:08.200 --> 00:10:10.600
The first term is
positive, that's

00:10:10.600 --> 00:10:13.820
the money you make
on the next unit.

00:10:13.820 --> 00:10:17.260
The second term is negative
because, by definition,

00:10:17.260 --> 00:10:18.940
the demand curve's
downward sloping.

00:10:18.940 --> 00:10:20.920
There's no given goods
anymore in this class.

00:10:20.920 --> 00:10:23.040
Demand may be on a test
but not in reality.

00:10:23.040 --> 00:10:26.740
The demand curve's
downward sloping, OK?

00:10:26.740 --> 00:10:29.010
So this term is negative.

00:10:29.010 --> 00:10:30.770
Now once again,
I'm writing delta

00:10:30.770 --> 00:10:31.980
but really it's derivative.

00:10:31.980 --> 00:10:33.855
So this is all increment--
this is all-- this

00:10:33.855 --> 00:10:35.030
is sort of epsilon changes.

00:10:35.030 --> 00:10:37.280
This is Q0, OK?

00:10:37.280 --> 00:10:38.870
This is sort of epsilon changes.

00:10:38.870 --> 00:10:41.390
But the bottom line is, for
an epsilon change in price

00:10:41.390 --> 00:10:42.660
you get--

00:10:42.660 --> 00:10:46.120
for an epsilon
change in quantity

00:10:46.120 --> 00:10:48.820
you get the price
on the unit you

00:10:48.820 --> 00:10:50.550
sell minus the money you lost.

00:10:50.550 --> 00:10:53.350
And then you too can
no longer sell, OK?

00:10:53.350 --> 00:10:57.960
This is the key intuition
of monopoly math.

00:10:57.960 --> 00:10:58.737
The k-- yeah?

00:10:58.737 --> 00:11:00.404
AUDIENCE: What's that
equation equal to?

00:11:00.404 --> 00:11:02.720
That [INAUDIBLE]

00:11:02.720 --> 00:11:05.370
JONATHAN GRUBER: This is
your marginal revenue.

00:11:05.370 --> 00:11:06.820
I just did it graphically.

00:11:06.820 --> 00:11:09.030
That's your marginal revenue.

00:11:09.030 --> 00:11:10.760
You just see that
from the graph, OK,

00:11:10.760 --> 00:11:13.183
and I just rewrote it here, OK?

00:11:13.183 --> 00:11:15.600
So basica-- or for those of
you into calculus, if you just

00:11:15.600 --> 00:11:20.280
differentiate, just-- if those
of you who have your calculus,

00:11:20.280 --> 00:11:25.950
you could just write, you
know, dR dQ, d revenue dQ, OK,

00:11:25.950 --> 00:11:26.860
what do you get?

00:11:26.860 --> 00:11:31.620
You get P plus dP dQ
times Q. That's just

00:11:31.620 --> 00:11:37.350
the derivative of revenue
with respect to quantity, OK?

00:11:37.350 --> 00:11:40.660
So let's think
intuitively about what's

00:11:40.660 --> 00:11:43.750
going on here because this
is very, very important.

00:11:43.750 --> 00:11:47.110
What's going on here
is to sell another unit

00:11:47.110 --> 00:11:49.360
you have to lower your price.

00:11:49.360 --> 00:11:51.670
You're working your way
down your demand curve.

00:11:51.670 --> 00:11:53.920
And therefore, it
offsets the benefit

00:11:53.920 --> 00:12:00.120
you get from selling
another unit, OK?

00:12:00.120 --> 00:12:03.780
I like to call this
the poisoning effect.

00:12:06.870 --> 00:12:08.780
I mean, it's not
original to me but it's

00:12:08.780 --> 00:12:11.930
a term that I've heard use that
I like, the poisoning effect.

00:12:11.930 --> 00:12:14.850
The idea is that to
sell another unit,

00:12:14.850 --> 00:12:16.700
I have to poison
myself a little bit

00:12:16.700 --> 00:12:21.632
by lowering the price on all
the previous units I sold.

00:12:21.632 --> 00:12:23.840
If I want to go out in the
market and force consumers

00:12:23.840 --> 00:12:25.970
to buy one more unit, I've
got to lower the price

00:12:25.970 --> 00:12:30.050
on all the units which
offsets money I used to make.

00:12:30.050 --> 00:12:33.540
So that's why we call it a
sort of poisoning effect.

00:12:33.540 --> 00:12:37.590
Now, why doesn't a competitive
firm face this issue?

00:12:37.590 --> 00:12:39.293
Why are we just
bringing this up now?

00:12:39.293 --> 00:12:41.293
Why does a monopoly firm
face a poisoning effect

00:12:41.293 --> 00:12:42.585
and a competitive firm doesn't?

00:12:42.585 --> 00:12:44.626
Or alternatively, another
way to ask the question

00:12:44.626 --> 00:12:46.500
is, in what situation
would a monopoly firm

00:12:46.500 --> 00:12:48.930
not face a poisoning effect?

00:12:48.930 --> 00:12:50.531
Yeah?

00:12:50.531 --> 00:12:53.140
AUDIENCE: Actually,
in a [INAUDIBLE]

00:12:53.140 --> 00:12:59.622
in a competitive
firm [INAUDIBLE]

00:12:59.622 --> 00:13:00.580
JONATHAN GRUBER: Right.

00:13:00.580 --> 00:13:02.205
They're not-- that's
[INAUDIBLE] right.

00:13:02.205 --> 00:13:03.930
The competitive firm's
the price taker.

00:13:03.930 --> 00:13:07.410
But in particular, even
though the price taker,

00:13:07.410 --> 00:13:11.240
why when they sell more quantity
is there no poisoning effect?

