this new marginal
revenue function.

00:25:50.790 --> 00:25:53.123
Otherwise, it's the same sort
of analysis we did before.

00:25:55.470 --> 00:25:58.040
So this should be doable
with some practice.

00:25:58.040 --> 00:26:03.520
Now, the key-- a key concept
here that we need to think

00:26:03.520 --> 00:26:06.020
about, that comes to question,
you might have asked yourself

00:26:06.020 --> 00:26:07.160
at some point--

00:26:07.160 --> 00:26:09.650
you might have said,
well, if monopolists

00:26:09.650 --> 00:26:12.140
are the only firm in the
market, why don't they

00:26:12.140 --> 00:26:14.520
just charge whatever they want?

00:26:14.520 --> 00:26:15.692
Why do they have to--

00:26:15.692 --> 00:26:18.150
why are they sort of constrained
by the sort of mathematics

00:26:18.150 --> 00:26:19.650
we've done before?

00:26:19.650 --> 00:26:23.370
And to answer this, let's turn
to the concept of market power.

00:26:25.910 --> 00:26:28.280
The market power
of monopolists we

00:26:28.280 --> 00:26:32.270
will define as their ability
to charge price greater

00:26:32.270 --> 00:26:34.760
than marginal cost.

00:26:34.760 --> 00:26:37.060
Your ability to charge price
greater than margin cost

00:26:37.060 --> 00:26:38.180
is your market power.

00:26:38.180 --> 00:26:40.490
In other words, competitive
firms have no market power.

00:26:40.490 --> 00:26:41.907
They have to charge
a price that's

00:26:41.907 --> 00:26:43.260
the same as their marginal cost.

00:26:43.260 --> 00:26:45.890
And that's why
they make no money.

00:26:45.890 --> 00:26:49.180
Monopolists have
market power, OK?

00:26:49.180 --> 00:26:51.310
So now let's return
to the condition

00:26:51.310 --> 00:26:53.110
for profit maximization.

00:26:53.110 --> 00:26:55.180
We said that
marginal revenue can

00:26:55.180 --> 00:26:59.200
be rewritten as
price times 1 plus 1

00:26:59.200 --> 00:27:03.910
over the elasticity
of demand, right?

00:27:03.910 --> 00:27:06.145
That equals marginal cost.

00:27:09.250 --> 00:27:14.330
So we can rewrite this as
marginal cost over price

00:27:14.330 --> 00:27:20.110
equals 1 plus 1 over the
elasticity of demand.

00:27:20.110 --> 00:27:23.680
And this is the monopolist's
market power condition.

00:27:23.680 --> 00:27:25.400
So if we define the market--

00:27:25.400 --> 00:27:27.775
so we can define something
we call a markup.

00:27:30.280 --> 00:27:32.500
Casually we can call it
profits, but technically it's

00:27:32.500 --> 00:27:37.250
the markup, OK, as
the percentage markup

00:27:37.250 --> 00:27:40.640
a monopolist can
make as p minus MC

00:27:40.640 --> 00:27:45.810
over p, how much of the price
is actually a markup over cost?

00:27:45.810 --> 00:27:47.640
It's sort of an
intuitive concept.

00:27:47.640 --> 00:27:49.440
So basically, how
much of the money

00:27:49.440 --> 00:27:53.110
you get for the unit is a markup
as a share of the money you

00:27:53.110 --> 00:27:55.020
get?

00:27:55.020 --> 00:28:00.480
Then that is simply--
that is equal to minus 1

00:28:00.480 --> 00:28:03.590
over the elasticity of demand.

00:28:03.590 --> 00:28:07.810
So the monopolist markup is
equal to 1 over-- minus 1

00:28:07.810 --> 00:28:11.490
over the elasticity of demand.

00:28:11.490 --> 00:28:14.720
So if the elasticity of
demand is negative infinity,

00:28:14.720 --> 00:28:17.440
that is a perfectly
competitive market.

00:28:17.440 --> 00:28:19.510
Then the markup is what?

00:28:19.510 --> 00:28:22.140
0, just like a competitive firm.

00:28:22.140 --> 00:28:26.630
Competitive firms have
to charge marginal cost.

00:28:26.630 --> 00:28:29.630
But as demand gets
more inelastic

00:28:29.630 --> 00:28:32.960
the monopolist gains
power to mark up the price

00:28:32.960 --> 00:28:33.620
and make money.

00:28:36.150 --> 00:28:38.790
And this answers our
question of why monopolists

00:28:38.790 --> 00:28:40.320
aren't infinitely powerful.

00:28:40.320 --> 00:28:42.660
What is the limiting
factor of monopolists?

00:28:42.660 --> 00:28:45.400
It's not other firms
producing their good.

00:28:45.400 --> 00:28:47.150
What's the limiting
factor on monopolists?

00:28:47.150 --> 00:28:47.770
Yeah?

00:28:47.770 --> 00:28:50.187
AUDIENCE: How much more will
they compete with [INAUDIBLE]

00:28:50.187 --> 00:28:52.610
JONATHAN GRUBER: Yeah,
it's other products.

00:28:52.610 --> 00:28:56.515
So think about a
monopolist in insulin.

00:28:56.515 --> 00:28:57.890
They can charge
whatever the hell

00:28:57.890 --> 00:29:01.550
they want, right, because
basically there's nothing else

00:29:01.550 --> 00:29:02.637
to buy.

00:29:02.637 --> 00:29:04.220
Well, maybe multiple
insulin products,

00:29:04.220 --> 00:29:07.460
but imagine one
insulin product, OK?

00:29:07.460 --> 00:29:09.170
So nothing constrains
the monopolist.

00:29:09.170 --> 00:29:10.878
He should charge an
infinite price up to,

00:29:10.878 --> 00:29:13.820
like, what Congress
will put up with, OK?

00:29:13.820 --> 00:29:16.040
But if you think about
a monopolist in a good

00:29:16.040 --> 00:29:21.820
where there's a substitute-- so
if I'm the monopolist in gum,

00:29:21.820 --> 00:29:24.740
if I'm a gum-opolist,
OK, then I'm

00:29:24.740 --> 00:29:26.330
constrained by how
much people want

00:29:26.330 --> 00:29:30.140
to-- eventually people just
substitute the candy, OK?

00:29:30.140 --> 00:29:32.120
Anything-- so I'm
constrained not

00:29:32.120 --> 00:29:34.910
by competitors in my
market, but by the fact

00:29:34.910 --> 00:29:38.250
that consumers can
substitute to other goods.

00:29:38.250 --> 00:29:39.860
So what's the limit
on monopolists?

00:29:39.860 --> 00:29:42.830
Consumers, we're the
limit on monopolists.

00:29:42.830 --> 00:29:45.470
Our willingness to put up
with that good relative

00:29:45.470 --> 00:29:47.210
to other goods, i.e.

00:29:47.210 --> 00:29:50.300
Our elasticity of
demand, is the only thing

00:29:50.300 --> 00:29:54.300
limiting monopolists, OK?

00:29:54.300 --> 00:29:56.952
So basically, there is market
discipline to monopolists.

00:29:56.952 --> 00:29:58.910
Even though they're the
only provider of a good

00:29:58.910 --> 00:30:01.040
they're still subject
to market discipline.

00:30:01.040 --> 00:30:04.010
It's just the discipline
doesn't come from other firms,

00:30:04.010 --> 00:30:08.360
it comes from consumers, OK?

00:30:08.360 --> 00:30:11.150
So a great example of
this is let's look,

00:30:11.150 --> 00:30:15.350
if you go on-- at least as of
last year, if you go on Amazon

00:30:15.350 --> 00:30:19.250
and look at the
prices of two goods

00:30:19.250 --> 00:30:21.230
that you've probably
had to consume

00:30:21.230 --> 00:30:25.580
in high school, Huckleberry
Finn and Great Gatsby, two books

00:30:25.580 --> 00:30:27.600
that many of you had to
consume in high school.

00:30:27.600 --> 00:30:28.975
You had to read
Huckleberry Finn,

00:30:28.975 --> 00:30:30.890
you had to read Great Gatsby.

00:30:30.890 --> 00:30:32.600
They're both
comparable lengths--

00:30:32.600 --> 00:30:33.920
Great Gatsby is a
little shorter I think,

00:30:33.920 --> 00:30:35.120
but they're both
comparable lengths.

00:30:35.120 --> 00:30:36.920
The production cost--
the marginal cost

00:30:36.920 --> 00:30:39.740
to produce them is probably
pretty comparable, OK?

00:30:39.740 --> 00:30:41.750
But if you go on
Amazon, Huck Finn

00:30:41.750 --> 00:30:44.735
costs $4 and the Great
Gatsby costs $16.

00:30:47.340 --> 00:30:49.400
Now why is this?

00:30:49.400 --> 00:30:50.720
Why is this, anyone know?

00:30:50.720 --> 00:30:53.110
Why does Great Gatsby
cost four times as much?

00:30:53.110 --> 00:30:55.640
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] it
was banned [INAUDIBLE]

00:30:55.640 --> 00:30:57.140
JONATHAN GRUBER:
That's interesting.

00:30:57.140 --> 00:30:58.380
That's not enough to explain.

00:30:58.380 --> 00:30:59.360
It's not banned
in enough places,

00:30:59.360 --> 00:31:00.860
fortunately, to explain that.

00:31:00.860 --> 00:31:03.540
What else is going
on, anyone know?

00:31:03.540 --> 00:31:05.648
Yeah, in the red shirt, yeah?

00:31:05.648 --> 00:31:07.690
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
competitive-- it has, like,

00:31:07.690 --> 00:31:09.148
has no copyright infringement.

00:31:09.148 --> 00:31:10.190
JONATHAN GRUBER: Exactly.

00:31:10.190 --> 00:31:13.370
The Great Gatsby still
has copyright protection.

00:31:13.370 --> 00:31:16.940
That is, only people who get
permission from the great--

00:31:16.940 --> 00:31:21.370
from William Scott
Fitzgerald's descendants--

00:31:21.370 --> 00:31:26.290
F. Scott Fitzgerald, I'm sorry,
descendents get to produce it.

00:31:26.290 --> 00:31:31.260
They have a monopoly on the
good that is The Great Gatsby.

00:31:31.260 --> 00:31:36.150
Huck Finn, it turns out that 75
years after an author's death

00:31:36.150 --> 00:31:38.940
copyright protection expires.

00:31:38.940 --> 00:31:41.640
F. Scott Fitzgerald hasn't
been dead for 75 years,

00:31:41.640 --> 00:31:43.250
Mark Twain has.

00:31:43.250 --> 00:31:45.300
So Huck Finn can now
be produced by anyone.

00:31:45.300 --> 00:31:47.592
You can go out tomorrow and
produce a copy of Huck Finn

00:31:47.592 --> 00:31:49.190
and sell it.

00:31:49.190 --> 00:31:52.190
So we think probably Huck
Finn should be produced

00:31:52.190 --> 00:31:54.500
in a pretty competitive market.

00:31:54.500 --> 00:31:56.450
That is, basically
the $4 you pay

00:31:56.450 --> 00:31:58.992
for Huck Finn should be roughly
the cost of producing a book.

00:31:58.992 --> 00:32:00.742
OK, now no market's
perfectly competitive,

00:32:00.742 --> 00:32:02.300
a little markup but not much.

00:32:02.300 --> 00:32:06.070
Whereas The Great Gatsby, it's
not limited by competition.

00:32:06.070 --> 00:32:07.820
But it is limited by
the fact that if they

00:32:07.820 --> 00:32:09.920
try to charge $500
for Great Gatsby

00:32:09.920 --> 00:32:12.830
teachers would assign
something else, OK?

00:32:12.830 --> 00:32:13.790
There's still a limit.

00:32:13.790 --> 00:32:16.100
It's only $16, that's
not a whole lot for one

00:32:16.100 --> 00:32:18.770
of the great works
of literature, OK?

00:32:18.770 --> 00:32:19.670
It's still only $16.

00:32:19.670 --> 00:32:21.200
So why is it only $16?

00:32:21.200 --> 00:32:22.783
Because it's limited
by the fact there

00:32:22.783 --> 00:32:25.490
are other great works of
literature people can turn to.

00:32:25.490 --> 00:32:27.660
So Huck Finn is limited
by the competition

00:32:27.660 --> 00:32:30.030
within the market for the--

00:32:30.030 --> 00:32:32.170
across producers producing
some homogeneous good.

00:32:32.170 --> 00:32:34.260
It's probably a pretty close to
the competitive market, right?

00:32:34.260 --> 00:32:36.910
It's pretty easy to just set up
a shop and produce Huck Finn,

00:32:36.910 --> 00:32:39.432
whereas The Great Gatsby
has this extra effect which

00:32:39.432 --> 00:32:40.890
is copyright
protected, so its only

00:32:40.890 --> 00:32:42.830
limited by the
elasticity of demand.

00:32:42.830 --> 00:32:44.742
Yeah?

00:32:44.742 --> 00:32:47.080
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] be
like, [INAUDIBLE] like,

00:32:47.080 --> 00:32:49.580
the effect of, like, when you
increase price again, and even

00:32:49.580 --> 00:32:51.910
more with piracy, in a sense?

00:32:51.910 --> 00:32:54.510
Like, if, like, when you have,
like, a really, like, expensive

00:32:54.510 --> 00:32:56.820
good it leaves, like,
more incentive to steal?

00:32:56.820 --> 00:32:57.640
JONATHAN GRUBER:
That's a great point.

00:32:57.640 --> 00:32:58.620
So the elasticity
of demand, I should

00:32:58.620 --> 00:33:00.360
say the elasticity of
demand for that good,

00:33:00.360 --> 00:33:02.860
where one of the substitutes
could be an illegal substitute.

00:33:02.860 --> 00:33:04.280
That's a good point.

00:33:04.280 --> 00:33:06.960
OK, so let's go on and
talk about the next topic

00:33:06.960 --> 00:33:10.803
I want to cover today, which
is how do we-- because now we

00:33:10.803 --> 00:33:12.720
have a new set of tools
we've developed that's

00:33:12.720 --> 00:33:15.600
really cool which lets
us ask the question,

00:33:15.600 --> 00:33:19.380
not just what do monopolies do,
but how do we feel about it?

00:33:19.380 --> 00:33:22.350
That is, we can now turn to
talking about the welfare

00:33:22.350 --> 00:33:24.860
effects of monopoly.

00:33:24.860 --> 00:33:26.570
What are the welfare
effects of monopoly?

00:33:26.570 --> 00:33:30.260
How do we feel about monopoly?

00:33:30.260 --> 00:33:32.760
Well, let's start with
the standard case,

00:33:32.760 --> 00:33:34.760
that is the case we've
covered so far as opposed

00:33:34.760 --> 00:33:38.000
to a case I'll cover
in a minute, OK?

00:33:38.000 --> 00:33:42.230
And let's look at
figure 11-5, which

00:33:42.230 --> 00:33:47.450
is the example we just solved
for, the example where demand

00:33:47.450 --> 00:33:53.420
equals 24 minus Q and
cost is 12 plus Q squared.

00:33:53.420 --> 00:33:54.980
So here we sh--

00:33:54.980 --> 00:33:56.210
once again what do we do?

00:33:56.210 --> 00:33:58.980
We set marginal cost
equal to marginal revenue.

00:33:58.980 --> 00:34:01.070
So they sell 6 units.

00:34:01.070 --> 00:34:03.620
We then say, what price
permits them to sell 6 units?

00:34:03.620 --> 00:34:05.360
The price of 18.

00:34:05.360 --> 00:34:08.060
So the equilibrium
is at a price of--

00:34:08.060 --> 00:34:12.500
is that e little m,
little m for monopoly, OK?

00:34:12.500 --> 00:34:17.350
They sell 6 units
at a price of 18.

00:34:17.350 --> 00:34:20.620
Well at that equilibrium,
what's consumer surplus?

00:34:20.620 --> 00:34:25.300
It's A, the area under the
demand curve, above the price.

00:34:25.300 --> 00:34:30.400
So consumer surplus is area
A. What's producer surplus?

00:34:30.400 --> 00:34:35.949
It's B plus D, the area below
the price above the supply

00:34:35.949 --> 00:34:37.870
curve, but only for the
units that are sold.

00:34:40.389 --> 00:34:46.929
So the consumer gets A, the
producer gets B plus D, OK?

00:34:46.929 --> 00:34:51.940
But C plus E is
not our units that

00:34:51.940 --> 00:34:55.179
are not sold for which
the marginal-- for which

00:34:55.179 --> 00:34:59.040
the willingness to pay is above
the willingness to supply.

00:34:59.040 --> 00:35:01.122
And what do we call those units?

00:35:01.122 --> 00:35:03.205
Units that are not sold--
someone raise their hand

00:35:03.205 --> 00:35:03.880
and tell me--

00:35:03.880 --> 00:35:06.213
units that are not sold for
which the willingness to pay

00:35:06.213 --> 00:35:08.220
is above the
willingness to supply?

00:35:08.220 --> 00:35:09.050
Yeah?

00:35:09.050 --> 00:35:09.390
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:35:09.390 --> 00:35:10.307
JONATHAN GRUBER: Loss.

00:35:10.307 --> 00:35:12.670
Those are units,
that's an inefficiency.

00:35:12.670 --> 00:35:17.560
Those units that are not sold
that efficiently should be.

00:35:17.560 --> 00:35:19.180
That is, we've broken--

00:35:19.180 --> 00:35:20.720
this our first example ever.

00:35:20.720 --> 00:35:23.620
This is a super exciting
moment of breaking

00:35:23.620 --> 00:35:25.928
the first fundamental
theorem of welfare economics.

00:35:25.928 --> 00:35:27.970
The first fundamental
theory of welfare economics

00:35:27.970 --> 00:35:32.800
was that the equilibrium,
the competitive equilibrium

00:35:32.800 --> 00:35:34.150
maximizes welfare.

00:35:34.150 --> 00:35:35.980
Well, that's no longer true.

00:35:35.980 --> 00:35:40.410
Here we have an equilibrium
that comes out of competition.

00:35:40.410 --> 00:35:43.830
It's what the market
delivers, but it

00:35:43.830 --> 00:35:45.487
doesn't maximize welfare.

00:35:45.487 --> 00:35:47.070
There's a dead weight
loss, and that's

00:35:47.070 --> 00:35:49.100
because the market's
imperfectly competitive.

00:35:49.100 --> 00:35:51.060
This is our first
ever example of what

00:35:51.060 --> 00:35:54.980
we call a market failure.

00:35:58.658 --> 00:36:00.200
And that's what,
from my perspective,

00:36:00.200 --> 00:36:01.735
makes economics fun.

00:36:01.735 --> 00:36:03.110
If there were no
market failures,

00:36:03.110 --> 00:36:05.690
if all markets functioned the
way we said they function, then

00:36:05.690 --> 00:36:08.065
basically we could have been
largely done with the course

00:36:08.065 --> 00:36:09.613
by now.

00:36:09.613 --> 00:36:11.030
What makes this
all interesting is

00:36:11.030 --> 00:36:12.822
markets don't function
the way we said they

00:36:12.822 --> 00:36:14.600
function in that extreme case.

00:36:14.600 --> 00:36:17.840
And therefore, a
market failure is

00:36:17.840 --> 00:36:22.070
defined as a case where the
market equilibrium does not

00:36:22.070 --> 00:36:24.510
maximize social welfare.

00:36:24.510 --> 00:36:26.780
So whenever the
market equilibrium

00:36:26.780 --> 00:36:29.300
does not maximize
social welfare,

00:36:29.300 --> 00:36:31.960
you've got a market failure.

00:36:31.960 --> 00:36:33.788
In the perfectly
competitive case

00:36:33.788 --> 00:36:36.080
we didn't have a failure
because the market equilibrium

00:36:36.080 --> 00:36:37.480
maximized welfare.

00:36:37.480 --> 00:36:39.130
That's not true here.

00:36:39.130 --> 00:36:42.370
Now the market equilibrium
does not maximize welfare.

00:36:42.370 --> 00:36:44.680
Therefore, it's
a market failure.

00:36:44.680 --> 00:36:46.480
Hint, what's exciting
about that to me

00:36:46.480 --> 00:36:49.235
is that means there might be a
potential role for policy, OK?

00:36:49.235 --> 00:36:50.860
So far in this course,
the government's

00:36:50.860 --> 00:36:51.740
just been a bad guy.

00:36:51.740 --> 00:36:53.990
Its done nothing but set
mean minimum wages and things

00:36:53.990 --> 00:36:56.020
like that, and terrible
price ceilings.

00:36:56.020 --> 00:36:57.520
But in fact, as
we'll see next time,

00:36:57.520 --> 00:36:59.687
this starts to introduce
the role for the government

00:36:59.687 --> 00:37:01.180
as a good guy, OK?

00:37:01.180 --> 00:37:04.500
Now, what makes-- to
drive this situation home,

00:37:04.500 --> 00:37:08.730
make this more interesting,
let's contrast that to the more

00:37:08.730 --> 00:37:12.180
realistic case of
price discrimination,

00:37:12.180 --> 00:37:15.900
or potentially more realistic
case of price discrimination.

00:37:15.900 --> 00:37:19.560
Now what happens if we
don't force the monopolist

00:37:19.560 --> 00:37:21.780
to only charge one price?

00:37:21.780 --> 00:37:25.530
What if we allow the monopolist
to charge different prices

00:37:25.530 --> 00:37:28.880
to different consumers?

00:37:28.880 --> 00:37:30.440
Here's a cool
conclusion actually,

00:37:30.440 --> 00:37:32.620
kind of crazy conclusion.

00:37:32.620 --> 00:37:36.468
If monopolists can perfectly
price discriminate,

00:37:36.468 --> 00:37:38.260
that is that they can
sell a separate price

00:37:38.260 --> 00:37:43.710
for every consumer, then
monopoly is welfare maximizing.

00:37:43.710 --> 00:37:46.270
If monopolists can set a perfect
price for every consumer,

00:37:46.270 --> 00:37:49.580
then monopoly does
maximize social welfare.

00:37:49.580 --> 00:37:51.680
To see that, simply
look at figure 11-6.

00:37:55.690 --> 00:37:59.980
Now let's take a perfectly
price discriminating monopolist.

00:37:59.980 --> 00:38:03.190
Let's think about what--
this prices they've set.

00:38:03.190 --> 00:38:08.115
Well, essentially what they're
going to do is set price where?

00:38:08.115 --> 00:38:09.490
A price discriminating
monopolist

00:38:09.490 --> 00:38:13.000
is going to set the price
for each unit to what?

00:38:13.000 --> 00:38:13.845
Yeah?

00:38:13.845 --> 00:38:14.720
AUDIENCE: The demand.

00:38:14.720 --> 00:38:16.580
JONATHAN GRUBER: The demand,
the willingness to pay.

00:38:16.580 --> 00:38:18.320
If you're perfectly
price discriminating,

00:38:18.320 --> 00:38:20.840
you will screw
consumers to the max.

00:38:20.840 --> 00:38:22.010
And how do you do that?

00:38:22.010 --> 00:38:25.870
By delivering them no surplus.

00:38:25.870 --> 00:38:28.040
By taking all the
surplus for yourself.

00:38:28.040 --> 00:38:31.450
So for the first
unit, you charge 5.

00:38:31.450 --> 00:38:33.010
For the second
unit, you charge 4.

00:38:33.010 --> 00:38:36.240
And for the sixth
unit you charge 18.

00:38:36.240 --> 00:38:39.660
Now, the [INAUDIBLE]---- now the
previous monopolist stopped

00:38:39.660 --> 00:38:40.620
at 6.

00:38:40.620 --> 00:38:42.000
Why do he stop at 6?

00:38:42.000 --> 00:38:45.240
Because the sale of the seventh
unit would have lost him money.

00:38:45.240 --> 00:38:47.670
He would've had to lower the
price on all previous units.

00:38:47.670 --> 00:38:49.170
But the price
[INAUDIBLE] monopolist

00:38:49.170 --> 00:38:51.060
has no poisoning
effect because he

00:38:51.060 --> 00:38:53.880
doesn't have to lower the
price on the previous units.

00:38:53.880 --> 00:38:55.650
He can say for
that seventh unit,

00:38:55.650 --> 00:38:59.325
I'm going to sell
that one at 17.

00:38:59.325 --> 00:39:00.700
I'm going to make
17, and I'm not

00:39:00.700 --> 00:39:02.242
going to lose any
money because I can

00:39:02.242 --> 00:39:04.410
keep the other prices the same.

00:39:04.410 --> 00:39:06.580
So with a perfectly price
discriminating monopolist,

00:39:06.580 --> 00:39:08.000
you get rid of the
poisoning effect.

00:39:08.000 --> 00:39:10.200
They can just march their
way down the demand curve,

00:39:10.200 --> 00:39:13.110
charging every consumer exactly
their willingness to pay.

00:39:13.110 --> 00:39:15.390
Therefore, they will
continue to produce

00:39:15.390 --> 00:39:17.400
until the competitive
equilibrium.

00:39:17.400 --> 00:39:19.650
They will continue to produce
until willingness to pay

00:39:19.650 --> 00:39:21.150
equals willingness to supply.

00:39:21.150 --> 00:39:23.500
But they will capture
all the surplus.

00:39:23.500 --> 00:39:25.830
So the new equilibrium
will be EC,

00:39:25.830 --> 00:39:29.070
the competitive equilibrium,
but the entire surplus

00:39:29.070 --> 00:39:31.870
goes to the monopolist.

00:39:31.870 --> 00:39:33.940
So the fascinating
case, there's--

00:39:33.940 --> 00:39:36.910
we maximize social welfare,
but only because we

00:39:36.910 --> 00:39:39.070
define social welfare
in this particular way,

00:39:39.070 --> 00:39:42.700
which is the simple sum of
consumer producer surplus.

00:39:42.700 --> 00:39:44.920
Here, producers get
all the surplus,

00:39:44.920 --> 00:39:47.790
therefore welfare is maximized.

00:39:47.790 --> 00:39:50.580
So a perfectly price
discriminating monopolist,

00:39:50.580 --> 00:39:55.650
OK, gets maximized
social welfare, OK?

00:39:55.650 --> 00:39:58.530
Now, there's two interesting
points to come out of this.

00:39:58.530 --> 00:40:01.980
Point one is this is a
cool way to understand

00:40:01.980 --> 00:40:05.557
why there's a dead
weight loss for monopoly.

00:40:05.557 --> 00:40:07.390
It's cool to understand
because you can see-

00:40:07.390 --> 00:40:10.015
you can focus on that point
E sub M and think about why

00:40:10.015 --> 00:40:12.640
the perfectly price [INAUDIBLE]
monopolist gets to sell another

00:40:12.640 --> 00:40:14.650
unit and the regular
monopolist doesn't.

00:40:14.650 --> 00:40:17.258
Because the regular monopolist
has the poising effect

00:40:17.258 --> 00:40:19.300
and the perfectly price
discriminating monopolist

00:40:19.300 --> 00:40:19.972
does not.

00:40:19.972 --> 00:40:21.430
So it's a good way
to sort of think

00:40:21.430 --> 00:40:24.210
about that intuition of
the poisoning effect.

00:40:24.210 --> 00:40:26.430
That's lesson one.

00:40:26.430 --> 00:40:29.748
Lesson two is, gee, we may
want to talk about definition

00:40:29.748 --> 00:40:32.040
of welfare that's not just
the sum of consumer producer

00:40:32.040 --> 00:40:33.920
surplus.

00:40:33.920 --> 00:40:36.720
A model of welfare that delivers
the fact that a producer that

00:40:36.720 --> 00:40:39.360
can screw every single consumer
out of any of their surplus

00:40:39.360 --> 00:40:41.430
is the best possible
outcome might not

00:40:41.430 --> 00:40:44.460
be a model we're
so happy with, OK?

00:40:44.460 --> 00:40:46.140
But that we can come back to.

00:40:46.140 --> 00:40:48.350
But for now it's a nice extreme.

00:40:48.350 --> 00:40:51.060
And in fact, in reality
no firm is perfectly

00:40:51.060 --> 00:40:53.320
price discriminating, OK?

00:40:53.320 --> 00:40:55.022
Amazon tried to be.

00:40:55.022 --> 00:40:56.730
There was a controversy
a number of years

00:40:56.730 --> 00:41:00.810
ago where Amazon would set
your price according to your--

00:41:00.810 --> 00:41:03.930
what's the little, the string
of numbers address, IP address.

00:41:03.930 --> 00:41:07.590
They literally would set
prices by IP address.

00:41:07.590 --> 00:41:09.330
They'd literally
say, well you know,

00:41:09.330 --> 00:41:12.060
you're coming from an IP address
that's, for example, you're

00:41:12.060 --> 00:41:13.192
in a high-high income area.

00:41:13.192 --> 00:41:14.400
I'm going to charge you more.

00:41:14.400 --> 00:41:15.720
You're in a
university, therefore

00:41:15.720 --> 00:41:17.053
you need this book for a course.

00:41:17.053 --> 00:41:19.620
Therefore, I'm going to
charge you more, et cetera.

00:41:19.620 --> 00:41:22.890
That, they got busted and
that was found illegal.

00:41:22.890 --> 00:41:25.650
But just because you can't
perfectly price discriminate

00:41:25.650 --> 00:41:30.000
doesn't mean we don't have lots
of examples of partial price

00:41:30.000 --> 00:41:30.700
discrimination.

00:41:30.700 --> 00:41:33.325
So what are examples in the real
