But like, but if you
live locally you can

00:47:38.200 --> 00:47:40.570
decide whether to go or not.

00:47:40.570 --> 00:47:43.450
And then probably the most
interesting recent example

00:47:43.450 --> 00:47:45.710
is Tesla.

00:47:45.710 --> 00:47:48.430
So during-- I feel like, did
I tell you guys the Tesla

00:47:48.430 --> 00:47:49.990
hurricane story yet?

00:47:49.990 --> 00:47:50.990
I don't think so, right?

00:47:50.990 --> 00:47:53.160
OK, so during the
hurricane in Florida--

00:47:53.160 --> 00:47:55.190
Irma, I guess it was?

00:47:55.190 --> 00:48:00.350
In Florida, Tesla-- so Tesla
so two cars, two models,

00:48:00.350 --> 00:48:03.350
the cheaper model and
the more expensive model.

00:48:03.350 --> 00:48:05.780
And the more expensive
model had some nice doodads,

00:48:05.780 --> 00:48:09.020
but most importantly the
battery lasted longer.

00:48:09.020 --> 00:48:11.060
The cheaper model
was like 300 miles,

00:48:11.060 --> 00:48:13.610
the more expensive model
was like 500 miles.

00:48:13.610 --> 00:48:19.460
During hurricane Irma, Tesla
as a gesture of goodwill said,

00:48:19.460 --> 00:48:21.740
hey guys who drive
the cheap car,

00:48:21.740 --> 00:48:23.720
you can now drive 500 miles.

00:48:23.720 --> 00:48:26.420
And they're like, what the
hell, it's the same battery?

00:48:26.420 --> 00:48:30.250
Tesla said, well it turns
out, it's the same battery.

00:48:30.250 --> 00:48:32.000
The only difference
is a piece of software

00:48:32.000 --> 00:48:34.710
that we can turn off or on.

00:48:34.710 --> 00:48:36.920
So why did Tesla do that?

00:48:36.920 --> 00:48:41.810
Why did Tesla have a piece of
software they turn off or on

00:48:41.810 --> 00:48:45.230
and turn it off for some
people to make them drive less?

00:48:45.230 --> 00:48:46.660
Why did they do that?

00:48:46.660 --> 00:48:47.950
There's someone else involved.

00:48:47.950 --> 00:48:49.592
Can anyone tell me
about what Tesla

00:48:49.592 --> 00:48:51.800
thought, meaning besides
the, oh, must be an asshole.

00:48:51.800 --> 00:48:52.300
What else?

00:48:52.300 --> 00:48:53.930
What's the other--
what's the kind of--

00:48:53.930 --> 00:48:55.520
what's Tesla's thought process?

00:48:55.520 --> 00:48:58.270
Actually, it was
perfect economics.

00:48:58.270 --> 00:48:58.780
Yeah?

00:48:58.780 --> 00:48:59.300
AUDIENCE: Price discrimination.

00:48:59.300 --> 00:49:00.670
JONATHAN GRUBER: Right,
it's price discrimination.

00:49:00.670 --> 00:49:01.697
But how?

00:49:01.697 --> 00:49:04.030
How are you price discriminating
by making some people--

00:49:04.030 --> 00:49:05.170
yeah?

00:49:05.170 --> 00:49:09.018
AUDIENCE: You can make a
500 mile car more expensive.

00:49:09.018 --> 00:49:10.060
JONATHAN GRUBER: Exactly.

00:49:10.060 --> 00:49:11.743
It's like first class.

00:49:11.743 --> 00:49:13.660
You're basically saying,
I want to charge more

00:49:13.660 --> 00:49:15.112
for a better product.

00:49:15.112 --> 00:49:16.820
I can't charge more
for the same product,

00:49:16.820 --> 00:49:19.840
so if I give everyone 500
miles I can't charge more.

00:49:19.840 --> 00:49:23.950
But by making one product
better I can separate demand.

00:49:23.950 --> 00:49:26.620
I can sell the expensive product
to the low elasticity of demand

00:49:26.620 --> 00:49:28.480
consumers and the less
expensive to the high

00:49:28.480 --> 00:49:29.470
elasticity of demand.

00:49:29.470 --> 00:49:33.370
But it's actually the same damn
product, I just did it as a way

00:49:33.370 --> 00:49:35.090
to price discriminate.

00:49:35.090 --> 00:49:37.930
So Tesla, in an
effort to be nice,

00:49:37.930 --> 00:49:40.760
screwed themselves by revealing
that they had been actually

00:49:40.760 --> 00:49:42.625
falsely screw-- you
know screwing consumers.

00:49:42.625 --> 00:49:44.500
It's not [INAUDIBLE]----
it's good economics.

00:49:44.500 --> 00:49:46.190
It makes total sense.

00:49:46.190 --> 00:49:48.950
OK, this actually
follows one last example.

00:49:48.950 --> 00:49:52.120
When the first laser
printers came out,

00:49:52.120 --> 00:49:54.320
OK, it turned out
that you could buy one

00:49:54.320 --> 00:49:57.740
for home that was like half
the price one for office.

00:49:57.740 --> 00:49:59.990
And someone took them apart
and found the one for home

00:49:59.990 --> 00:50:02.600
was the one for the office
plus an extra piece that

00:50:02.600 --> 00:50:03.500
made it go slower.

00:50:06.540 --> 00:50:08.113
And they did that
simply because they

00:50:08.113 --> 00:50:10.530
knew the office guys were less
price elastic than the home

00:50:10.530 --> 00:50:11.270
guys.

00:50:11.270 --> 00:50:12.810
So they wanted an expensive
one-- so they said,

00:50:12.810 --> 00:50:13.810
the office one's faster.

00:50:13.810 --> 00:50:14.580
Isn't this cool?

00:50:14.580 --> 00:50:16.955
It was faster because they
didn't add an extra piece that

00:50:16.955 --> 00:50:18.247
made to go slower, OK?

00:50:18.247 --> 00:50:19.330
And that's the same thing.

